</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/30916" pageId="264" pageNumber="265" start="Figure 15" startId="F15">
<paragraph pageId="264" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">Figure 15.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Say" authorityYear="1830" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Elaphrus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="264" pageNumber="265" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuliginosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">Elaphrus fuliginosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Say. Why the great naturalist Thomas Say gave this eastern species the name 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">fuliginosus</emphasis>
(sooty) is not evident. It may refer to the mirrors on the elytra which gives the impression that the animals are dirty. Members of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Elaphrus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="264" pageNumber="265" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">Elaphrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have the ability to produce stridulating chirps by rubbing rows of bristles on the dorsal surface of the abdomen against two areas of parallel ridges on the ventral surface of the elytra. The sound is produced when the beetle is under stress.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
